      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#191817;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling in Stafford Heights 2026
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Stafford Heights is an established north Brisbane family suburb with Kedron Brook access and strong Westfield Chermside proximity. Here is what sellers need to know before listing in 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Stafford Heights sits approximately nine kilometres north of the Brisbane CBD, straddling the Gympie Road corridor between Kedron and Chermside to the east and the wider northern suburbs to the west. It is an established suburb with generous block sizes, good retail access and a practical family character that draws buyers who have been priced out of Kedron or who want more land than Chermside's denser housing stock provides. Selling in Stafford Heights in 2026 means understanding the specific comparison buyers are running when they arrive at this suburb, because those comparisons define what positioning and pricing decisions you need to make.</p>

      <p>Westfield Chermside, one of Brisbane's largest shopping destinations, sits approximately two to three kilometres from most Stafford Heights addresses via Gympie Road. Kedron Brook Bikeway runs along the suburb's southern boundary, giving residents direct access to the linear green corridor that connects west to McDowall and east toward the airport precinct. Stafford Heights State School serves the local catchment and is a relevant factor for buyers with primary-school-age children. The suburb's internal streets are quieter and more residential in character than the Gympie Road frontage, and buyers consistently prioritise properties on those internal streets over equivalent homes with main-road positioning.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Stafford Heights</h2>
      <p>The dominant buyer in Stafford Heights in 2026 is the family that has been comparing this suburb against Kedron and Chermside and has concluded that Stafford Heights offers better land content at a more accessible price point. Kedron has tightened significantly over the past three years, and buyers who want a genuine family home on a block large enough for a pool and outdoor entertaining area find that Stafford Heights consistently delivers that combination more affordably. These buyers arrive with clear priorities: land, school catchment, Westfield Chermside proximity and a reasonable commute path. They have been tracking the market and they know the comparable sales.</p>

      <p>Buyers whose daily routine involves the northern health and services corridor form a second consistent group. Workers at Prince Charles Hospital or in the Stafford business park area find that Stafford Heights sits at a practical point relative to their workplace. The commute from Stafford Heights to either destination is short and manageable, which makes the suburb a natural target for that employment demographic. These buyers are not optimising for CBD proximity; they are optimising for the northern suburbs' own commercial and employment geography.</p>

      <p>Renovators who have identified that the suburb's price floor provides an entry point below what a renovated property at the same address could achieve represent a third buyer type. The proportion of unrenovated post-war homes in Stafford Heights remains significant, and buyers with the capacity and intent to renovate are finding opportunity here. This buyer profile tends to move cautiously but acts decisively when the purchase price and renovation budget align with their projections.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Stafford Heights</h2>
      <p>Kedron Brook proximity is the most distinctive value driver in Stafford Heights, because the bikeway access is a meaningful lifestyle advantage that distinguishes this suburb from Stafford and other nearby alternatives. Properties within easy walking distance of the Kedron Brook entry points attract buyers who cycle, run or simply want their family to have green space access. This is not a marginal factor; it is a concrete differentiator that should be made prominent in any campaign for a well-positioned property.</p>

      <p>Block size is the second major driver. The buyers who choose Stafford Heights over Kedron are specifically choosing it for the land. A well-proportioned block with usable outdoor space consistently outperforms a compact site in the same street, and the marketing should quantify and explain the outdoor space in practical terms rather than leaving buyers to estimate it from floor plans or photography.</p>

      <p>Street character matters. Stafford Heights' quieter internal streets have an established, owner-occupied feel that is more appealing to family buyers than properties positioned on busier roads. The contrast between a quiet cul-de-sac and a Gympie Road frontage is stark, and buyers weight it accordingly. A property on a settled internal street commands a premium that is consistent and meaningful.</p>

      <p>Westfield Chermside proximity is valued as practical amenity rather than prestige amenity. The buyers in this market are families who want access to major retail, restaurants and services without a long drive. This is an everyday convenience factor that resonates strongly with the practical buyer profile that dominates Stafford Heights.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Stafford Heights home for sale</h2>
      <p>Stafford Heights buyers are practical and value-led. They are comparing what they can buy here against what an equivalent budget achieves in Kedron, and they arrive at the property with clear expectations about condition relative to price. Kitchen condition is the first and most important thing they assess. A kitchen that functions well and is presented cleanly will hold its value in negotiations. A kitchen that is clearly dated and worn will invite discounting, because the buyer is already estimating the replacement cost before they leave the property. A targeted cosmetic update, if it is achievable within budget, consistently returns more than its cost in the final sale price.</p>

      <p>Outdoor space presentation is particularly important in this suburb, because the block size is part of the value proposition. A well-presented, clearly defined outdoor space that demonstrates how the land functions in daily use reinforces the buyer's instinct to pay for the block. An outdoor area that is neglected, overgrown or ambiguous undermines confidence in the property's condition overall and invites a lower assessment.</p>

      <p>A pre-sale building and pest inspection completed before the campaign provides control over the condition narrative. Stafford Heights' housing stock includes many older homes where building and pest findings are common. Completing the inspection, addressing what is economically worthwhile to address and providing the report to buyers from the start of the campaign removes a significant source of buyer-side uncertainty and reduces the leverage available for mid-campaign price renegotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Stafford Heights</h2>
      <p>Stafford Heights follows the north Brisbane seasonal pattern, with two reliable selling windows each year. The autumn window from late February through May consistently produces strong results for family homes, because buyers who have been watching the market through December and January arrive in March and April with genuine urgency and a defined sense of what they need. Listing volume in autumn is typically lower than spring, which means a well-prepared property encounters less competition from other sellers and can attract concentrated buyer attention.</p>

      <p>The spring window from September through November is the higher-volume market, with more listings and more buyers active simultaneously. A well-positioned Stafford Heights property launched in late September sits at the point of maximum buyer activity. The risk is that competing listings in October and November dilute the field. Sellers who want to avoid competing against a busier spring market sometimes find that a late August or early September launch captures the returning buyer appetite before the broader spring volume arrives.</p>

      <p>School-year enrolment timing drives a portion of Stafford Heights buyer activity from July through September. Families targeting Stafford Heights State School need to confirm their address before the following year's enrolment deadline, which creates a time-sensitive buyer segment that responds to campaigns marketed with explicit catchment information. A campaign that addresses this segment directly, rather than leaving buyers to verify catchment independently, will capture more of their attention and can produce stronger early-campaign competition.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Stafford Heights</h2>
      <p>Well-presented Stafford Heights homes, correctly priced against recent local sales and against the Kedron and McDowall comparables that buyers are running in parallel, typically sell within 28 to 45 days. The buyer pool in this suburb is motivated but not as deep as in Kedron or Nundah, which means pricing precision is more important than in tighter markets. A buyer comparing Stafford Heights against Kedron will identify overpricing immediately and will return to Kedron or wait for a correction. Getting the price right from the campaign launch is the most effective way to ensure competitive tension and a timely result.</p>

